### Fields

Simple Fields

* id (PK)  
* name  
* description  
* function: summarization, planning, etc.  
* scope: input, processing, output (1 to many)  
* status: active, deprecated, experimental  
* owner: system or a user that created it  
* authored\_by: (system vs. user-generated)  
* usage\_stats: number of times used, last used  
* visible: If the task should be visible to the users or only be used by the system  
* example executions of the task: Show the corresponding inputs and outputs (through FK)  
  * Show the best examples (thumbs up)  
  * Show problematic examples (thumbs down)  
* Dependencies (through FK)  
  * KUs or KMs  
  * KUs (Tools, Directives, Tables)  
* Embedding to make it searchable (on description)

### Manually Interacting with Tasks (Workbench Functionality)

* Test Mode  
  * Create an input for the tasks and see what’s the corresponding output  
* Modify Dependencies  
  * Change which directives are used

### Knowledge Modules

Often tasks can form hierarchies based on how specific they are. Let’s show this with an example:

Text Summarizer   
	→ Log Event Summarizer   
		→ Palo Alto Event Summarizer   
			→ Palo Alto THREAT Event Summarizer  
			→ Palo Alto TRAFFIC Event Summarizer  
		→ Cisco Event Summarizer  
	→ Report Summarizer  
	…

* **Text Summarizer:** This is the highest-level task, responsible for general text summarization.  
* **Log Event Summarizer:** This is a more specific type of summarization focusing on summarizing log events.  
* **Palo Alto Event Summarizer:** This further narrows down to summarizing events from Palo Alto systems.  
* **Palo Alto THREAT Event Summarizer:** This is the most specific task, focused on summarizing THREAT events from Palo Alto.

To better facilitate re-use, we can make use of Knowledge Modules. A KM for Text Summarization can be used by all types of summarization tasks. Note that the relationships between Tasks is just used here for illustration purposes. Tasks depend only on KUs. And KUs may build upon each other.

### Relationships

* Many-to-many with KUs and KMs

## Knowledge Units (KUs)

This is the base class essentially for the different types of Knowledge Units (KUs) that we will expand next. 

#### Common Components of a Knowledge Unit (KU)

| Field | Description |
| :---- | :---- |
| `id` | Unique identifier (UUID or auto-incremented ID) |
| `name` | Human-readable name |
| `description` | Short summary of the KU's purpose or use case |
| `type` | Enum: `directive`, `table`, `tool` — used for filtering and icons |
| `authored_by` | `system` or `user-generated` — indicates origin |
| `owner` | User or system entity that created or owns this KU |
| `created_at` | Timestamp of creation |
| `updated_at` | Timestamp of last update |
| `usage_stats` | Number of times used, last used timestamp |
| `visibility` | Public/private/internal — for tenanting or scoping |
| `tags` | Optional labels or categories (e.g., `threat-intel`, `network`) |
| `dependencies` | List of other KU IDs it references (self-referential) |
| `embedding_vector` | (Optional) Vector for semantic search on description/content |
| `source_document_id` | (Optional) ID for provenance, if extracted from a doc or system integration |
| `version` | As we make updates it’s good to be able to go back and view and compare earlier versions |

#### Optional UI-Related Fields

| Field | Description |
| :---- | :---- |
| `status` | Enum: `active`, `deprecated`, `experimental` — for filtering and status badges |
| `editable` | Boolean — whether this KU is editable by the current user |

## Tables

Tabulated lists of information that can be referenced to by directives and used by tasks. Some examples of tables include: 

* List of admins  
* List of crown jewels  
* Domain controllers  
* Internal IP ranges  
* Departing employees  
* Allowed listed software

List can only include Vector information to be searchable via embedding similarity. Examples are: 

* Runbooks  
* Historical Alerts  
* Task Specific Examples

### Fields

* id (PK)  
* name  
* description  
* data\_type (tabular vs vector-based)  
* embedding\_metadata (optional if vector)  
* source\_document\_id to track provenance for tables auto-generated from a doc (good for audit/logging).  
* authored\_by (system vs. user-generated)  
* Embedding to make it searchable (on description)  
* Embedding on content (periodically updated, good for infrequent updates)

### Relationships

* many-to-many with Task  
* many-to-many with Directive

## Directives

These are short paragraphs that represent advice, an instruction, a suggestion, or information to be used while executing a task. Directives can reference other directives and Tables. 

Example: 

* “When using Threat Intelligence, always give higher priority to inputs from VirusTotal that have at least 10 VTs matching”   
* “If the user is part of the following list, it’s ok for them to access our Internal Database as long as it's part of the allowed list of Databases. 

  List of allowed user:  
  ${admin\_users\_table}

  List of allowed databases:  
  ${database\_ips\_table}  
  ” 

### Fields

* id (PK)  
* name  
* description  
* content (text)  
* dependencies to other KUs  
* authored\_by (system vs. user-generated)  
* source\_document\_id to track provenance for tables auto-generated from a doc (good for audit/logging)  
* Embedding to make it searchable  
* Embedding on content (periodically updated, good for infrequent updates)

### Relationships

* many-to-many with Task  
* self-referencing many-to-many for directive chaining  
* many-to-many with Table

## Tools

Tasks can use tools to achieve their goals. All tools are defined using the Model Context Protocol (MCP) standard. Users can define new Tools and allow tasks to use them.  New tools need to be explicitly added to tasks in order to be usable by them. 

### Type-Specific Metadata (for Tool KUs)

- `mcp_endpoint`  
- `integration_id` (optional, for audit/inventory)

### Fields

* id (PK)  
* name  
* Description  
* Mcp\_endpoint  
* authored\_by (system vs. user-generated)  
* source\_document\_id to track provenance for tables auto-generated from a doc (good for audit/logging)  
  * This is typically via an Integration

### Relationships

* many-to-many with Task  
* Open question: Should directives rely on Tools?   
  * Thought: Avoid letting Directives directly depend on Tools. Tools imply execution. Directives should remain declarative and static. If a Directive must reference dynamic data, it should do so indirectly via a Task that calls a Tool.

## Documents

Documents are unstructured text-based resources (e.g., PDFs, pasted text, extracted web content) that can be referenced by Tasks or Directives. They are primarily used to provide supporting information, such as policy documents, playbooks, or vendor manuals. Documents may be retrieved in full or chunked into segments and stored in a vector database for semantic retrieval (RAG workflows).

While Directives typically express concise logic or instructions, Documents serve as broader, referenceable sources of contextual knowledge.

### Fields

* id (PK)  
* name  
* description  
* document\_type: pdf, markdown, html, plaintext  
* content\_source: upload, API, integration  
* authored\_by: system vs. user-generated  
* source\_url (optional)  
* embedding\_metadata (e.g., chunking strategy)  
* vectorized: boolean  
* embedding\_on\_content: generated for semantic search  
* created\_at / updated\_at  
* visibility: public/private/internal

### Relationships

* many-to-many with Task  
* many-to-many with Directive  
* Referenced by other KUs (e.g., through `${document_name}` placeholders)
